<span id="freeTextContainer3760000584795978777">The strength of this book is the author&apos;s familiarity with scholarship of the ancient and medieval west. He does a marvelous job of outlining the mindset of both periods, eschewing the usual stereotypes. The weakness of the book is its Eurocentric and top-down approach to the subject. Although the author gives a nod to non-western uses of spices, the book is really about spices as a costly export from distant fplacds. At its best it is a history of the orientalist viewpoint as seen through the l</span>
  <span id="freeText3760000584795978777" style="display:none">The strength of this book is the author's familiarity with scholarship of the ancient and medieval west. He does a marvelous job of outlining the mindset of both periods, eschewing the usual stereotypes. The weakness of the book is its Eurocentric and top-down approach to the subject. Although the author gives a nod to non-western uses of spices, the book is really about spices as a costly export from distant fplacds. At its best it is a history of the orientalist viewpoint as seen through the lens of cuisine. At its weakest, it veers (admittedly only intermittently) into orientalitism itself. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3760000584795978777" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

