        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3457068044" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12679783005641397245">History through the lens of one particular thing is a wonderful way to get both the big picture and the telling details. Mark Kurlansky&apos;s Cod or Barbara Freese&apos;s Coal are exceptional reads, and to the shelf I now add Turner&apos;s Spice. Who knew that the mummy of Rameses II had peppercorns up his nose? Or that the island of Manhattan was the loser&apos;s prize in the 17th century spice wars, when the Dutch claimed the Moluccas, where nutmeg, cinnamon and mace grew? Spice permeates trade, literature, reli</span>
  <span id="freeText12679783005641397245" style="display:none">History through the lens of one particular thing is a wonderful way to get both the big picture and the telling details. Mark Kurlansky's Cod or Barbara Freese's Coal are exceptional reads, and to the shelf I now add Turner's Spice. Who knew that the mummy of Rameses II had peppercorns up his nose? Or that the island of Manhattan was the loser's prize in the 17th century spice wars, when the Dutch claimed the Moluccas, where nutmeg, cinnamon and mace grew? Spice permeates trade, literature, religion - every aspect of life - and Turner tells the story so elegantly!</span>
